&#xa0;
[normal]Written e[bold]vidence submitted [bold]by[bold] the Serious Hazards of Transfusion Haemovigilance Scheme[bold] (BTO0029)[bold]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This paper describes the national strategy for surveillance of adverse events related to blood transfusion and the resulting improvements in patient safety. Blood transfusion is very safe and effective when used appropriately.
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Questions about blood safety emerged following the appearance of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome and discovery of its related virus (human immunodeficiency virus, HIV) in the 1980s.  Multiply transfused haemophilia patients treated with factor concentrates made from pooled plasma were noted
[normal] in the late 1970s
[normal] to develop hepatitis transmitted from these products. 
[normal]There was also concern that serious and potentially lethal errors (incompatible blood transfusions) were not reported.
[normal] Therefore many countries decided to set up vigilance programmes. 
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The European Union
[normal] published a series of Blood Safety Directives (2002-2005) which were transposed into the UK Blood Safety and Quality Regulations (BSQR) in 2005. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) was appointed as the Competent Authority to implement the EU Safety Directives. The BSQR focus on serious adverse reactions and events which must be reported by law to the EU. 
[normal]The MHRA requires reporting of all serious reactions such as transfusion-transmitted infection or haemolysis, but also serious adverse events caused by a process failure in the quality management system in Blood Establishments and hospital transfusion laboratories regardless of whether the component was transfused, but the legislative remit extends only to the point where the transfusion laboratory reponsibility ends. Adverse events involving only clinical staff are not reportable under EU legislation but constitute the largest group of 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reports including avoidable or delayed transfusion, near miss events and mistakes with anti-D immunoglobulin administration to RhD negative women during and after pregnancy.
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Haemovigilance is defined (by the International Haemovigilance Network)  as surveillance procedures covering the whole transfusion chain, from collection of blood and its components to follow-up of recipients, intended to collect and assess info
[normal]rmation on unexpected or undesir
[normal]able effects resulting from the therapeutic use of labile blood products and to prevent their occurrence or recurrence. 
[normal]  Blood transfusion is a multistep process involving several different professional groups who need to work closely together (nursing staff, laboratory staff, medical staff, porters). The
[normal] 
[normal]UK
[normal] national haemovigilance scheme, Serious Hazards of Transfusion (
[normal]SHOT
[normal]) was set up in 1996
[normal], prior to the introducion of the EU Directives, 
[normal] and now has reported annually for 16 years
[normal] (17
[normal]th
[normal] report currently being prepared)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] is funded by the 4 UK Blood Services and is affiliated to the Royal College of Pathologists.  Its activities are overseen by a steering group whose membership includes representatives from the Royal Colleges (medical and nursing) and other specialist societies.
[normal] A full list is available on the 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] website (
[normal]www.shotuk.org/home/terms-of-reference
[normal] ).
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] collects and analyses information on transfusion reactions and adverse events from all healthcare organisations in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] that are involved in blood transfusion.  
[normal]This includes transfusion of red cells, plasma, cryoprecipitate and platelet concentrates.  
[normal]SHOT
[normal] works collaboratively with other bodies with responsibility for transfusion safety (e.g. the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), the National Blood Transfusion Committee
[normal] (set up in 2001)
[normal] and its counterparts in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, the Advisory Committee on the Safety of Blood, Tissues and Organs (SaBTO), the National Patient Safety Agency, and the Department of Health Blood Policy
[normal] 
[normal]Unit).
[normal]  Reports required by the BSQR are submitted to the MHRA through their statutory SABRE online reporting system since 2005.  
[normal]SHOT
[normal]’s online reporting system shares a common portal – some events are only MHRA-reportable, others, particularly 
[normal]many 
[normal]clinical 
[normal]incidents
[normal] may only be 
[normal]SHOT
[normal]–reportable and others require reporting to both schemes.  Reporters now enter demographic data once, and 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] and the MHRA are working towards a combined system.  The 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] Annual reports for 2011 and 2012 include a chapter describing the MHRA reports.  Meetings take place to reconcile the data (e.g.transfusion-related deaths, transfusion-transmitted infections).
[normal]  
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal]’s
[normal] 
[normal]mission is to improve patient safety in blood transfusion in the following ways: 
[normal]7)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reporting to SHOT was initially voluntary but is now required by several professional bodies
[normal] (Clinical Pathology Accreditation, Nursing and Midwifery Council)
[normal] and is mandatory for clinicians in line with the General Medical Council’s  standard for Good Medical Practice
[normal], and the Francis Report
[normal].  
[normal]8)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reporting to 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] has increased steadily over the 17 years of reporting
[normal] (data for 2013 currently under analysis)
[normal].
[normal] In 
[normal]2012 99.5
[normal]% of all NHS Hospitals, Trusts and Health Boards were registered to report to 
[normal]SHOT
[normal], and 97.8% submitted reports (
[normal]total reports for 2012=
[normal]3545)
[normal].
[normal]9)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reports fall into 
[normal]four
[normal] main categories
[normal] (cumulative number of reports 1996-2012 = 11570)
[normal]:
[normal]10)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Overall, about half of all reported events are a result of mistakes. 
[normal]Most of these do not result in serious consequences for the patient.
[normal] Each year the report includes learning points and recommendations for changes in practice.  
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reporting has been instrumental in changing practice both at the Blood 
[normal]Servic
[normal]es and in hospital
[normal] laboratories and clinical areas
[normal]. 
[normal]  
[normal]SHOT
[normal] thus alerts the NHS to transfusion safety issues which can be addressed in order to reduce the risks.
[normal]11)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Examples of risk reduction by 
[normal]Blood [bold]Service[bold]s[bold] as a result of 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reporting and recommendations are:
[normal]12)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reports are classified according to a 
[normal]set of 
[normal]definitions (
[normal]based on those published by
[normal] the I
[normal]nternational 
[normal]Society of B
[normal]lo
[normal]od T
[normal]ransfusion) and are analysed by members of a working expert group including transfusion specialists, hospital consultants and senior laboratory scientists whose expertise covers the different types of incidents. Analysis yields 
[normal]trends and 
[normal]features leading to the overall major recommendations in each annual report (such as weaknesses in patient identification, failure to perform the final bedside checks), specific recommendations in the different incident groups  as indicated above, and learning points for laboratory and clinical staff to improve their practice. The Annual Report is published at an annual symposium held in July where the findings are presented and discussed
[normal] together with relevant transfusion topics
[normal].
[normal] In addition 8-12 page booklets are produced alternate years summarising the main lessons, ‘Laboratory Lessons’ and ‘Clinical Lessons’.  These are distributed at meetings and teaching sessions
[normal] and are available to download from the website in addition to the Annual Reports, their summaries and other resources
[normal].
[normal]13)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Changes in 
[normal]H[bold]ospital [bold]P[bold]ractice[bold] resulting from 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reporting
[normal]: 
[normal]14)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The demonstration every year that incorrect transfusions
[normal] (e.g. wrong blood group, or missing specific requirements for that patient)
[normal] make up the largest group of adverse events led to several initiatives.
[normal]15)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Summary of data from the 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] report for events reported in 2011 and 2012
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2011
[normal]2012
[normal]Deaths
[normal]8 (1 from delayed and inadequate transfusion, 3 transfusion-associated circulatory overload,  2 acute transfusion reactions, 1 infant with necrotising enterocolit
[normal]i
[normal]s
[normal])
[normal]9 (1 transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease
[normal]*
[normal], 2 haemolytic transfusion reactions, 6 transfusion-associated circulatory overload)
[normal]Major Morbidity
[normal]117
[normal]134
[normal]There had been no reports of transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease since 2001 and this death prompted a national review of practice with new recommendations and guidance (see Annual Report for 2012 for details at 
[normal]www.shotuk.org
[normal] )
[normal]16)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reporting has alerted the transfusion community that p
[normal]eople with sickle cell disease are at particular risk of adverse events, particularly haemolytic transfusion reactions with serious outcome (11/16, 68.8%
[normal] experiencing death or major morbidity
[normal] in the three years
[normal] 2010 to 2012).
[normal]17)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Patients receiving bone marrow transplants have been identified at risk for receiving wrong blood group transfusions leading to recommendations for better communication.
[normal]18)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mistakes occur because at every stage of the transfusion process the professionals involved do not 
[normal]always 
[normal]follow established procedures. This has been highlighted in 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reports and the recommendation made for a checklist to be used.
[normal]  This has not yet been widely adopted but is likely to improve safety of the key steps as has been demonstrated 
[normal]by introduction of the WHO checklist 
[normal]for surgery.
[normal]19)[bold]&#xa0; 
