[normal]Deaths where the transfusion was definitely
[normal] or partly
[normal] responsible numbered 8 in 2011 and 9 in 2012 and the incidence of major morbidity was 117 in 2011 and 134 in 2012.
[normal] This increase has occurred due to better recognition that patients can develop 
[normal]lung
[normal] complications related to transfusion, particularly transfusion-related acute lung injury and transfusion-associated circulatory overload. 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reporting has drawn attention to these events, and advised an amend
[normal]ment to the BCSH Guidelines on Administration of B
[normal]lood
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]omponents
[normal] to reduce the risks.
[normal] This addendum was published in 2012.
[normal]23)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Errors continue to put patients at risk, particularly failure to adhere to basic procedures for identification of the correct patient at the time of blood sampling and at the time of transfusion. Errors make up more than half of all events reported to 
[normal]SHOT
[normal].
[normal]  Human errors 
[normal]relating to patient identification 
[normal]can be reduced by bar-code technology
[normal] (recommended by 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] in
[normal] 2009
[normal])
[normal] to link patient identity to blood samples with a confirmation against the blood bag and wristband at the time of transfusion.  These methods have been demonstrated to reduce transfusion errors (evidence published from 
[normal]Oxford
[normal]) but the uptake by hospitals has been limited by the costs.
[normal]24)[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Key recommendations from SHOT Annual Reports for 2011 and 2012[bold]- ‘back to basics’[bold]:[bold]25)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal].
[normal]The full 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] reports can be found at 
[normal]www.shotuk.org/shot-reports/
[normal] together with the shorter summaries
[normal].
[normal]26)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] haemovigilance scheme is an international field leader
[normal] because it was one of the earliest, has detailed analysis and trending. T
[normal]he data 
[normal]are
[normal] widely used at international as well as national levels.  Many countries have developed haemovigilance schemes, particularly in 
[normal]Europe
[normal], but the International Haemovigilance Network encourages all countries to set this up.  It is difficult to compare data between countries as data collection 
[normal]and denominator data are variable
[normal].  
[normal]27)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] collects ‘near miss’ events where no harm came to the patient, but important lessons are learned from these observations. For example, for every wrong transfusion resulting from a wrong blood sample, there are about 100 ‘near miss’ events where the error was recognised
[normal] before any transfusion took place,
[normal] for example because the blood group previously recorded 
[normal]for the patient 
[normal]was different
[normal] to the one associated with the current blood sample
[normal].
[normal]28)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]SHOT
[normal] produces benchmarking data 
[normal]annually 
[normal]for all participants
[normal],
[normal] relating the number of reports to the 
[normal]size of the organisation as defined by the number of 
[normal]blood components issued, and grouped geographically.  These show that the range
[normal] of medians
[normal] is 0.69 to 1.21 for the number of reports per 1000 components issued
[normal] in the different sized organisations, with an overall range of 0 to 6.8
[normal] reports
[normal]. European and Canadian data are similar with 0.2 to 7.07 reports per 1000 units transfused or issued to hospitals.  A WHO Global Forum in November 2012 in association with the International Soiety of Blood Transfusion and the International Haemovigilance Network had representation from 46 countries. There is variable development of haemovigilance schemes hindered in many countries by lack of resources but also by a cultural fear of reporting adverse incidents.
